arch:property.oc:show_val: Blockage of the niches of the ‘bathroom’
North section: 0.68 m; West section: 0.48 m; South section: 0.50 m.

Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
North section: 0.66 m north south -by- 1.45 m east west. West section: 1.65 m north south -by- 0.43 m east west. South section: 0.50 m north south -by- 1.45 m east west.

Locus 59 is the blockage covering the niches of the bathroom. This blockage consists of hewn and dressed sandstone ashlars on the north, west, and south walls of the bathroom, above the niches and the channel. The ashlars both covered over the niches, and filled them in to some degree. They were removed, and so have all been measured and recorded. The niches were filled in with soil, including smaller architectural fragments such as opus sectile, then a large floor paver of ashlar was jammed in to cover the niche, and finally the ashlars were lined up to cover the niches to the point of the channel on the floor of the bathroom. The ashlars are dry-laid in roughly two courses and one row along each side of the bathroom. The blockage was most substantial on the north. As it appears that this blockage was in preparation for the dumping in the bathroom and anteroom, Locus 59 is phased with that event to Stage 5.
Full blockage, robbing out and dumping.
